  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and agreements aimed at combating money laundering. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) is the primary global organization that develops policies to fight money laundering and terrorist financing. Many countries have adopted anti-money laundering (AML) regulations based on FATF recommendations, including:\n\n1. Requiring financial institutions to conduct customer due diligence\n2. Monitoring and reporting suspicious transactions\n3. Maintaining records of financial activities\n4. Implementing know-your-customer (KYC) procedures\n5. Sharing information internationally to detect and prevent money laundering\n\nThe United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime and the Palermo Convention also provide international frameworks for addressing money laundering.\n\nMost developed countries have their own national laws that criminalize money laundering and impose significant penalties for violations. These laws typically require financial institutions to have robust compliance programs to detect and prevent illicit financial activities.",
